nairṛtya naiṛtya bhimukhassamapādasthito dakṣiṇakaramuṣṭiṃ muṣṭhiṅ kṛtvā madhyamātarjanyau kuñcayet / khaḍgākāreṇa khaḍgakāreṇa \HT\ misreads khadgakāreṇa, and emends khadgākāreṇa (with d, not ḍ). saṃsthāpya vāmakaraṃ kaṭipradeśe pradese dhārayedvāmatarjanīṃ vāmantarjjanīṁ kuñcayitvā nirṛte nisater \HT\ reads niṛter and emends nairṛter. rāvāhanamudrā / asyāemend anayā? But see asyā again in next §. \HT\ accepts asyā. eva mudrāyā mudrayā \HT\ misreads mudrāyā which he emends to mudrayā. vāmakaraṃ kaṭideśe kaṭidese 'vasthitaṃ khaḍgamudrā khadgamudrā \HT\ just reads khaḍgamudrā. Cf. preceding §. It seem \HT\ had the opposite understanding from ours of which akṣaras represent ḍ and d. / nirṛteḥ nirsateḥ \HT\ reads nirṛteḥ and emend nairṛteḥ. What is the proper reading of the akṣara we tentatively read rsa? Can it be an alternative form of ṛ? samayamudrā / āvāhana āvāhana- avāhana- mudrāyāstarjanīṃ prasārya visarjanamudrā / mantraḥ mantra
